# Branch Hygiene

This repo is now a solo-dev workflow. Two simple rules, enforced by hooks, replace the old master-plan chunk machinery:

1. **Never commit on `main` or `master`.** Hooks deny it.
2. **Branch off the latest work tip — wherever HEAD currently is — not stale `main`.** The helper script defaults to this.

The 2026-04 chunk-ID system (`P0-BE-1`, `P2-FE-3`, branch-name-must-contain-chunk-ID, no-mixed-chunks-since-main, etc.) is **retired**. The master plan that motivated it is complete. Anything still referencing chunk IDs in old plan docs is historical.

---

## Starting a new branch

Use the helper. It branches off whatever you're standing on right now — so if you're on a smoke branch with newer unmerged work, the new branch stacks on top automatically instead of reaching back to stale `main`:

```bash
./scripts/check-branch-chunk.sh --create <branch-name>
```

Examples:

```bash
./scripts/check-branch-chunk.sh --create fix/oauth-token-leak
./scripts/check-branch-chunk.sh --create feat/branched-chains-phase-1
./scripts/check-branch-chunk.sh --create docs/runbook-refresh
```

The branch name is yours to pick. Suggested prefixes (purely conventional, not enforced): `feat/`, `fix/`, `chore/`, `docs/`, `refactor/`, `smoke/`, `verify/`.

If you genuinely want the new branch off `origin/main` instead of HEAD (rare — only when you're starting truly independent work from a clean base), check out main first:

```bash
git fetch origin && git checkout origin/main
./scripts/check-branch-chunk.sh --create feat/something-independent
```

---

## Committing

Just `git commit` as usual. The hooks will block one thing and one thing only: committing directly on `main` or `master`. Anything else passes.

Commit message format is up to you. Recommended (purely conventional, not enforced): [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/) — `fix(scope): subject`, `feat(scope): subject`, etc.

---

## If a hook denies a commit on `main`

The error message tells you the recovery command. The short version:

```bash
./scripts/check-branch-chunk.sh --create <branch-name>
# branches off HEAD (= main in this case), checks out, re-run your commit
git commit -m "..."
```

---

## What the helper script does

`scripts/check-branch-chunk.sh`:

- **`--create <name>`** — creates and checks out `<name>` off current HEAD. That's it.
- **(no args)** — quick check: prints a warning if you're standing on `main` or `master`. Useful as a pre-flight before you start typing changes.
- **`--help`** — prints usage.

Old modes (`--create <CHUNK-ID> <slug>`, pre-flight chunk-ID validation, mixed-chunk detection) are gone.

---

## What the hooks enforce

Two enforcement layers, both call the script under the hood. Both deny only one situation: commits on `main` or `master`.

- **Cursor `beforeShellExecution`** (`.cursor/hooks/check-commit-branch.sh`) — fires when the Cursor agent runs `git commit` through the shell tool. Returns a deny payload with the recovery command.
- **Git `commit-msg`** (`.githooks/commit-msg`) — fires on every `git commit` regardless of who invoked it (agent shell, Cursor source-control panel, terminal, etc.). Activated per-clone via `./scripts/install-hooks.sh`.

If `.githooks/commit-msg` isn't installed yet (fresh clone), run `./scripts/install-hooks.sh` once. Idempotent.

---

## What this rule does NOT cover

- **PR titles, descriptions, or stacked-PR base branches.** Use whatever makes sense; GitHub's UI is fine.
- **Auto-rebasing.** Neither the script nor the hooks ever modify your branch. They only inspect.
- **CI enforcement.** Local pre-flight aid only. GitHub will merge whatever you push.

---

## Reference

- Script: `scripts/check-branch-chunk.sh` (`--help` for full usage).
- Setup: `scripts/install-hooks.sh` — run once per clone to enable the git `commit-msg` hook.
- Cursor hook: `.cursor/hooks/check-commit-branch.sh`, wired in `.cursor/hooks.json` under `beforeShellExecution` with matcher `\bgit\s+commit\b`.
- Git hook: `.githooks/commit-msg`, activated via `git config core.hooksPath .githooks` (done by `install-hooks.sh`).
